# Cursor Rules — Trading Exchange Platform

## Project Overview
Microservices crypto trading platform. Maven multi-module parent `crypto-exchange` with five Spring Boot 3 / Java 21 services and a React 18 + TypeScript frontend.

## Module Structure
```
auth/           → Authentication Service     (port 8081, org.serhiileniv.auth)
gateway/        → API Gateway                (port 8080, org.serhiileniv.gateway)
order-matching/ → Order Matching Service     (port 8082, org.serhiileniv.order)
wallet/         → Wallet Service             (port 8083, org.serhiileniv.wallet)
market-data/    → Market Data Service        (port 8084, org.serhiileniv.marketdata)
frontend/       → React SPA                  (port 3000, exchange-ui)
```

## Naming Conventions

### Java
- Packages: `org.serhiileniv.<module>` — no `crypto` prefix inside packages
- Main classes: `AuthApplication`, `GatewayApplication`, `OrderMatchingApplication`, `WalletApplication`, `MarketDataApplication`
- Services: `UserService`, `WalletService`, `OrderService`, `MarketDataService` — never prefix with module name
- Repositories: `UserRepository`, `WalletRepository`, `OrderRepository` — extend `JpaRepository`
- DTOs: `AuthResponse`, `WalletResponse`, `OrderRequest`, `OrderResponse` — suffix with Request/Response
- Events: `OrderPlacedEvent`, `OrderMatchedEvent`, `OrderCancelledEvent` — always include `eventType` field
- Controllers: `AuthController`, `WalletController`, `OrderController` — prefix `@RequestMapping("/api/v1/<resource>")`

### Spring app names (application.properties)
- `auth-service`, `api-gateway`, `order-matching-service`, `wallet-service`, `market-data-service`

### Kafka
- Topic: `order-events`
- Consumer groups: `wallet-group`, `market-data-group`
- Event discrimination: `eventType` field (STRING) — `ORDER_PLACED` | `ORDER_MATCHED` | `ORDER_CANCELLED`

### Docker containers
- `auth-service`, `api-gateway`, `order-matching-service`, `wallet-service`, `market-data-service`
- Infrastructure: `postgres`, `redis-auth`, `redis-market`, `kafka`, `zookeeper`, `pgadmin`

### Frontend (TypeScript/React)
- Components: PascalCase — `PlaceOrderPage`, `OrderBookPage`, `ToastContext`
- API functions: camelCase — `placeOrder`, `getWallets`, `cancelOrder`
- Types: PascalCase interfaces — `OrderResponse`, `WalletResponse`, `MarketDataResponse`
- Hooks: `use` prefix — `useToast`, `useAuth`

## Architecture Rules

### Gateway
- ALL requests enter through gateway (port 8080)
- JWT validated by `JwtAuthenticationFilter` before forwarding
- `userId` extracted from JWT claim and injected as `X-User-Id` header
- Services MUST read user identity from `X-User-Id`, never re-parse JWT (except wallet)
- Public routes: `/api/v1/auth/**`, `/api/v1/market-data/**`

### Auth Service
- BCrypt password hashing — never store plaintext
- Access token: 15 min TTL, contains `userId` claim
- Refresh token: 7 days TTL, stored in Redis (`redis-cache`), revocable on logout
- JWT secret key shared across: gateway, auth, order-matching, wallet — via `JWT_SECRET_KEY` env var

### Order Matching
- Order placement sequence: persist → publish OrderPlacedEvent → matchOrder() → publish OrderMatchedEvent (if matched)
- Matching engine uses pessimistic write lock on counterparty order queries
- BUY matches when buyPrice >= sellPrice; SELL matches when sellPrice <= buyPrice
- MARKET orders match any counterparty price

### Wallet (Saga Pattern)
- `ORDER_PLACED` → lock funds (quote currency for BUY, base for SELL)
- `ORDER_MATCHED` → settle trade: debitLocked from payer, deposit to receiver
- `ORDER_CANCELLED` → unlock funds
- Idempotency: check `ProcessedEvent` table before processing any Kafka event
- Symbol parsing: `BTC-USDT` splits on `/` or `-` → [base, quote]

### Market Data
- Consumes `ORDER_MATCHED` events only
- Updates: `lastPrice`, `high24h`, `low24h`, `volume24h`, `tradeCount24h`
- `priceChangePercent24h` = `(lastPrice - openPrice24h) / openPrice24h * 100`
- Cached in Redis (`redis-market`) with 10-minute TTL; evicted on every trade
- Daily reset at midnight UTC via `@Scheduled(cron = "0 0 0 * * *")`

## Code Style

### Java
- Use Lombok: `@Data`, `@Builder`, `@RequiredArgsConstructor`, `@Slf4j`
- Lombok before MapStruct in annotationProcessorPaths (order matters)
- `@Transactional` on service methods that write to DB
- Log with `log.info()`/`log.error()` — never `System.out.println`
- Return types: use DTOs from controllers, never expose entities directly

### Testing
- Unit tests: Mockito mocks only — no embedded DB, no Testcontainers
- Smoke tests (`*SmokeTest`): `@SpringBootTest` + `@MockBean` for infrastructure
- Always set `eventType` field in Kafka event test fixtures

### Frontend
- Access token: store in JS memory only (tokenStore), never localStorage — XSS mitigation
- Refresh token: localStorage — survives page refresh
- API calls: always via `apiClient` (Axios instance with interceptors)
- Errors: use `err.userMessage` (set by interceptor) over raw `err.message`
- Mutations: invalidate related queries on success

## Build Commands
```bash
mvn -B clean verify                              # full build + tests
mvn -B clean package -DskipTests                # build only
mvn -B test -pl wallet                           # single module tests
docker compose up --build                        # full stack
docker compose config                            # validate compose file
```

## Key Invariants — Never Break These
1. `JWT_SECRET_KEY` must be identical in gateway, auth, order-matching, wallet
2. All Kafka events must include `eventType` field — consumers switch on it
3. Wallet events must be idempotent — always check ProcessedEvent before acting
4. Lombok must come before MapStruct in annotationProcessorPaths
5. `ddl-auto=update` — no manual schema migrations, Hibernate manages schema
